#YearInPictures | December 2019 — Representative Jerrold Nadler of New York, chairman of the House Judiciary Committee, with committee members, lawyers and aides, reviewed the articles of impeachment against President Trump before publicly announcing them. Later in December, Trump became the 3rd president in history to be impeached. The New York Times was given rare behind-the-scenes access to photograph impeachment preparations, and @erinschaff took this photo ⁣
⁣
Every year, our photo editors sift through 365 days of photographs in an attempt to recapture and visually distill the year. To see the full collection of our Year in Pictures, tap the link in our bio, and check out our Story to look back on more of the best photos from 2019.⁣

“It almost feels like a cleansing of energy,” @mfairchild17 said of this Sugarplum Fairy variation in “George Balanchine’s The Nutcracker,” which is at @nycballet through January 5. “That’s maybe too new age, but it feels like an aura or something. Everything feels crystal clear, and I’ve cleared the space for myself.” The role, Megan’s first big part as a member of the corps de ballet, is one she’s grown into. It wasn’t always easy — especially the pas de deux, which comes later in the ballet, but, “it becomes a part of you,” she said. In this solo, Megan is accompanied by the pianist Stephen Gosling, who plays the famous Tchaikovsky music. Her approach to dancing is pure Balanchine: It pushes classical ballet past its boundaries. “You’re never on balance,” she told the #nytimes critic @giadk. “You never get totally on your leg. You fall away from it so it creates its own beauty. It has this breezy flow — like you’re being caught in the wind.” @emonhassan made this video for #SpeakingInDance, our weekly series exploring the world of #dance.

In a childless village, handmade dolls fill the void. As Japan’s population shrinks and ages, rural areas are emptying out. In the remote mountain village of Nagoro, the last children were born 18 years ago, and the elementary school closed its doors in 2012, shortly after the final 2 students completed 6th grade. But one resident, Tsukimi Ayano, 70, and her friends have brought the village back to life with some 350 giant handmade dolls, which outnumber the human residents by more than 10 to 1. The dolls are arranged around the village in various scenes evoking the real people who once lived there — they also participate in an annual recreated sports festival where the dolls take part in events like tug of war. “I wish there were more children because it would be more cheerful,” Tsukimi said. “So I made the children.” To read more about the village, tap the link in our bio. @nadiashiracohen took these photos.

Across the U.S. Chinese restaurants are closing — and the owners say that’s a good thing.  The “golden age” of Chinese cooking in America was the late 1960s and early 1970s, when a large number of Chinese, including many chefs and restaurateurs, immigrated to the country during China’s Cultural Revolution. But now these owners of Chinese-American restaurants are ready to retire and have no one to pass the business to. Their children, educated and raised in America, are pursuing professional careers that do not demand the same grueling labor as food service. “In some ways, the children are regaining the status of the first generation that they have lost while migrating,” said Jennifer Lee, a professor of sociology at Columbia University. “The goal has never been to continue those businesses.” For more on how economic mobility impacts the number of Chinese restaurants (and for some graphs that illustrate the trend), tap the link in our bio. @lrnlncstr took this photo at a Chinese restaurant, Eng’s, in Kingston, New York.

Only in New York would you find a reindeer traveling on public transit. Reindeer Richard was admiring the view on his way to be the star attraction at a Christmas party for children on Roosevelt Island. And one New Yorker thought nothing of it as she traveled, undisturbed and unimpressed, on the Manhattan tramway on December 3, 1977. This photo was taken by Chester Higgins Jr. For more vintage pictures from our archive, follow @nytarchives.

The best way to start a day off is with French toast. This French Toast Amandine recipe ups the flavors on the classic by using a rich bread like brioche or challah and adding sliced almonds. Top it with maple syrup or fruity jam for an elegant and easy holiday breakfast. To see more festive breakfast recipes from @nytcooking, tap the link in our bio.

Bronner’s Christmas Wonderland bills itself as the largest Christmas store in the world. The 115,000-square-foot superstore, about 80 miles north of Detroit, is a holiday destination, with some 2 million visitors each year. It’s open 361 days a year and has everything from 17-foot Santas to staff members who paint personalized messages onto little ornaments. To read more about the family business keeping the Christmas spirit alive year-round, tap the link in our bio. @jarodlew took these photos.

How did Taylor Swift write “Lover,” one of her most romantic songs ever? In the latest installment of #DiaryOfASong, @taylorswift explains to our pop music reporter @joecoscarelli how she got out of bed late at night, walked to her piano and recorded a voice memo of the chords and chorus of the song. She sent the clip to her producer, @jackantonoff, and he texted her back to “get on a plane.” They recorded “Lover” in the studio the next day. She discusses the song’s driving bass guitar riff, the lyrics she changed and the importance of the bridge and answers the question fans have been wondering: Doesn’t everyone leave their Christmas lights up till January? Tap the link in our bio to watch the full video.

We make too much and buy too much, but maybe there is a way not to waste too much. The designer Daniel Silverstein, aka Zero Waste Daniel, is certainly trying. @zerowastedaniel has set out to change industry norms by creating a company that is the antithesis of fast fashion — it’s trashion. His company makes 100% zero waste clothes using preconsumer, postproduction waste, which is a fancy way of saying he works with the fabrics that other designers and costume departments and factories would usually throw out. His studio is filled with scraps of found fabric that he sews into a variety of garments, which range from $25 for a patch to $595 for an anorak made from what used to be a New York City Sanitation Department tent. To read more about @zerowastedaniel’s mission and how he’s shaking up the fashion industry, tap the link in our bio. And make sure to follow @nytimesfashion for more on the intersection of climate change and fashion. @vincenttullo took this photo.

A student who found independence in dance. A refugee who runs a custom clothing shop. An immigrant who found a purpose in art therapy. A widow who adopted several foster children. A Dreamer who found her voice as an “accidental activist.” A man who stopped working to care for his son, who has autism, before receiving a lymphoma diagnosis. These are just a few of the stories from The New York Times Neediest Cases Fund, our annual campaign that raises money to help those facing tough times. To learn more, tap the link in our bio and check out our Story for more of these stories. @bnewmanphoto, @sandy_huffaker, @cgregoryphoto, @poynter_photo_co, @winniewow and @callakessler took these photos.

Amid a crisis in local news, more than 1,000 reporters, photographers, editors and other newspaper employees around the country lost their jobs this year. We talked to 8 journalists who had to leave newsrooms in 2019, as they reflect on the untold local stories left in their notebooks. Photographers who also lost their jobs captured the reporters (and their old press badges and notebooks) on their former beats. ⁣
⁣
Tap the link in our bio for the stories of Gabriel San Román from The Orange County Weekly; Gary Warner from The Bend Bulletin; Nanette Light from The Dallas Morning News; Wilborn P. Nobles III from The New Orleans Times-Picayune; Graig Graziosi from The Vindicator in Youngstown, Ohio; Allison Guinn from The Ledger in Lakeland, Florida; Julie Garcia from The Corpus Christi Caller Times (not pictured); and Anne Delaney from The Greeley Tribune in Greeley, Colorado (not pictured). Some have found new jobs in journalism, but others are still searching for their next story. @stoopdown, @joeklinephoto, @nhunsingerone, @mdemocker, William D Lewis and Scott Wheeler took these photos.⁣

Quarterback Joe Namath’s iconic fur coat. The 1958 championship that became known as the “Greatest Game Ever Played.” Odell Beckham Jr.’s infamous one-handed catch. Unforgettable coaches, players and fans. At 100 years old, the N.F.L. is still spectacularly popular in the U.S. across lines of gender, race, age, class and even politics. It may feel as if the league has always been this powerful, but for much of its early existence, pro football was a niche, regional sport. It didn’t take root nationally until the late 1950s. By 1965, pro football had replaced baseball as the country’s favorite sport. To look back at some of the N.F.L.’s most iconic moments in its 100-year history, tap the link in our bio. Photos by: Barton Silverman, Ernie Sisto, Keith Meyers, Al Bello/Getty Images, Henry Barr Collection/Diamond Images/Getty Images, Associated Press

Giving gifts? Amazing. Wrapping gifts? Panic-inducing. Our step-by-step guide on how to wrap any present — rectangular, round or anything else — will save you this holiday season. Tap the link in our bio to see our foolproof methods to make any gift look spectacular. Video by @tedandchelsea.

One of the most popular toys of the last decade, LOL Surprise! dolls, was created to compete with the YouTube unboxing videos that feature kids opening new toys and products. Much to the chagrin of parents who are bewildered by the trend of unboxing videos, many children today would rather watch YouTube kids unwrap products than play with toys of their own. But these pint-sized, candy-colored dolls come inside opaque packaging, so kids don’t know what they’re getting until the toy is fully unwrapped, making them perhaps the ultimate unboxing toy. Isaac Larian, the man behind the $5 billion toy juggernaut, is the founder and CEO of MGA Entertainment and familiar with creating a craze-inducing toy: His company created Bratz dolls. And now LOL dolls are outpacing the sales of Barbie, Pokémon, Nerf and Marvel action figures. To read more about how LOL Surprise! became the dopamine hit of a generation, tap the link in our bio. For more stories about parenting, follow @nytparenting. @kendrickbrinson took this photo.

Zoe Fishman eventually married her subway crush of four years. But after tragedy, she had to remember how to keep following her heart. Tap the link in our bio to read the full essay, and follow @nytfashion for more #ModernLove.

These latkes are the ultimate holiday comfort food. And this no-frills, no-fail recipe will give you beautifully browned potato pancakes — the greatest gift of all. Serve them while they’re still warm (and don’t skip the sour cream and applesauce!). To check out this recipe – and 21 other latke variations – tap the link in our bio. What’s your go-to holiday recipe? Photo by Romulo Yanes, with food styling by @vivianhlui.

How does @nytmag’s cover come together? Our video series will take you #BehindTheCover, where the magazine’s editor in chief, Jake Silverstein, and its design director, Gail Bichler, discuss this week’s cover story and explain how they arrive at the final product. This week’s story is about the growing home death-care movement, which rethinks the conventional ways we deal with the bodies of deceased loved ones. In working with artist @mrdeannecheuk, @gailbichler said, “We wanted to convey the feeling on the cover, rather than, specifically, the concept.” To read the cover story, tap the link in our bio, and follow @nytmag for more.

These cookies are a work of art. Really, they’re inspired by the brushstroke paintings of Ellsworth Kelly. Start with a sugar cookie base coated with royal icing and follow by painting bold red stripes of peppermint. Randomly arrange them on a plate and wait for your friends to snatch them up. To see more dazzling cookie recipes from @nytcooking just in time for last-minute holiday baking, tap the link in our bio. @conpoulos took this photo with recipe and food styling by @susanspungen and prop styling by @paigehicksnyc.

For his 47th stop on this year’s list of 52 Places to Go, our traveler spent the week exploring the west coast of New Zealand’s south island. “I could barely get through a single song on the “Lord of the Rings” soundtrack (I mean, what else would I be listening to?) without hitting another viewpoint so beautiful I had to stop.” Sebastian Modak, our #52Places columnist, reveled in nature, from the Punakaiki Pancake Rocks to Arthur’s Pass. Tap the link in our bio to read the full dispatch from New Zealand and follow @nytimestravel for more travel stories from around the world. @sebmodak took this photo of the Hokitika Gorge.

The police killed an average of 17 people every day in Brazil last year. But masked vigilantes – off-duty and retired police officers – are killing even more. These illegal militias operate in the shadows of a severe crackdown on crime by the Brazilian government, which has openly declared war on the gangs, thieves and drug dealers afflicting the nation. By their own admission, these militias regularly commit extrajudicial killings, targeting people they consider criminals, robbers and cop killers without so much as an arrest warrant. In their minds, they are delivering a public service. “I’ve killed more than 80 criminals in my time as a police officer,” one militia leader told our reporter. “I’m a hero to my people. They love me.” To read more about the violence in Brazil, tap the link in our bio. Tyler Hicks took this photo.

#YearInPictures | August 2019 — A watermelon-eating contest at a block party in the Marine Park section of Brooklyn. Block parties have a long history in New York City and, this summer, we sent 20 photographers to 65 parties across the city to capture New Yorkers eating, dancing and playing in the streets. @sarahblesener took this photo.⁣

See if you can spot Ernie Sisto, The New York Times photographer who took this photo, reflected in the ornament. Follow @nytarchives for more festive photos from our vault. #TBT
